
Parallelism is allowed only where identity, ordering and diagnostics remain deterministic.

Fast is good.
Repeatable is required.

The compiler uses interned identities, source locations, type-rendering context and diagnostic payloads across many stages. A parallel pass must explain how those identities are merged and remapped before later stages consume them.

## String-table principle

A build uses `StringTable` identity across config loading, frontend compilation, backend validation, output writing and diagnostic rendering.

Parallel workers may fork string tables only when their deltas are merged and remapped in deterministic order.
Tokens, headers, warnings, diagnostics, type-rendering contexts and module payloads must see stable IDs after the merge.

Full `StringTable` cloning and full-table merging remain available for true independent table boundaries.
They should not be used for ordinary parallel module compilation.

## Directory project compilation

Directory project compilation uses a shared string-table base.
Module jobs compile with local deltas over that immutable base.
After module compilation completes, the build system merges local suffixes in deterministic entry-path order and remaps module payloads when needed.

Stage 0 owns this build-boundary lifecycle.
The module frontend owns its own internal per-file fork/merge lifecycle before dependency sorting.
Don't blur those layers.

## Module inventory discovery

Multi-entry directory builds may run module inventory discovery in parallel only after a serial provider-free classification proves that no reachable import needs an external import provider or unsupported external-extension diagnostic.

That classification carries scanned Beanstalk source text forward so provider-free workers don't re-read the same files.

Provider-capable discovery stays serial for now because it mutates:

- external package registry
- provider cache
- resolution table
- shared diagnostic string table

Parallel provider-backed discovery needs deterministic provider deltas and ID remapping first.

## Source-file preparation

Inside one module, source files can be prepared in parallel.
Each file tokenizes and header-parses against a local string-table fork.
The module frontend merges file deltas back into the module table in deterministic input order before module-wide header aggregation, dependency sorting and AST construction.

Stage 1/2 scheduling can choose:

- serial preparation for tiny modules
- per-file Rayon for medium modules when source bytes justify it
- chunked Rayon for larger modules

Every strategy must produce ordered chunk-local results, then merge string-table deltas and remap tokens, headers, warnings and diagnostics in original source-file order.

`RAYON_NUM_THREADS` remains the external concurrency control.
The compiler doesn't create a custom frontend Rayon pool.

## Source loading reuse

Reachable-file discovery reuses Beanstalk source text read during import scanning when assembling `InputFile` values.
Files not scanned for imports, such as plain Markdown and Beandown assets, are loaded through a threshold-gated missing-source path.

Small miss sets stay serial.
Larger miss sets use Rayon, then rejoin in deterministic inventory order before header preparation sees them.

## AST body emission

AST body emission remains serial in production.

`AstEmitter` consumes a mutable `AstModuleEnvironment`, parses bodies through `ScopeContext` values backed by `Rc`/`RefCell` state, emits warnings and rendered-path usages through shared sinks and accumulates generic instantiation requests before concrete instances are emitted.

Locks would add churn without solving deterministic merge.
A safe parallel AST needs a real ownership split:

- immutable environment snapshot for worker reads
- worker-local string-table forks or pre-interned body symbols
- read-only lookup surfaces that are `Send`/`Sync`
- deterministic merge of warnings, rendered path usages, generic instantiation requests and emitted nodes
- a clear owner for the generic instance worklist

Until those preconditions exist, AST measurement should focus on stable timings and counters such as body-root counts, root scope arenas, generic templates/instances and const-template parse/fold time.

## Out of scope for this parallelism pass

HIR generation, borrow validation, backend lowering and Wasm lowering remain intentionally out of scope for the current frontend parallelism work.
They shouldn't be parallelised as follow-on cleanup to Stage 0 or file-preparation scheduling changes.

Each of those stages needs its own ownership analysis before parallel execution is safe.

## Common mistakes

- Merging string-table deltas in thread-completion order.
- Reusing full-table cloning for ordinary module jobs.
- Parallelising provider-backed discovery without deterministic provider deltas.
- Letting per-file preparation merge warnings or diagnostics out of source-file order.
- Adding locks around AST's mutable environment and calling that parallel-ready.
- Parallelising HIR or borrow validation just because token/header preparation became parallel.
- Dropping remap handling for diagnostics or type-rendering context.
